💬 Observations
XGBoost achieved strong performance on the Breast Cancer Wisconsin dataset, with an accuracy of approximately 97% and an AUC-ROC of approximately 99%. These results demonstrate that the model is highly effective at distinguishing between malignant and benign breast tumors.
The feature importance analysis reveals that the most influential features are related to the worst and mean values of concave points, perimeter, and radius. This is consistent with clinical knowledge — malignant tumors are typically characterized by larger, more irregularly shaped cell nuclei with more pronounced concavities along their boundaries. The fact that the model independently identifies these features as the most predictive serves as a strong validation of its learning process.
Despite a moderate class imbalance (62.7% benign vs 37.3% malignant), precision and recall remain high for both classes. The model achieves particularly strong recall for the benign class (~0.99), meaning it very rarely misclassifies benign tumors. Recall for the malignant class (~0.95) is also high, which is especially important in a medical context — missing a malignant diagnosis (false negative) carries significant clinical risk.
The ROC curve further confirms the model's robustness. With an AUC approaching 1.0, the model maintains excellent sensitivity across virtually all threshold levels, meaning it can be tuned for different clinical scenarios (e.g., prioritizing sensitivity over specificity when screening) without significant performance loss.
Overall, XGBoost proves to be a highly suitable algorithm for this classification task, offering both strong predictive performance and meaningful interpretability through its feature importance mechanism.
